  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Glucose: Brain, wound, kidney's best friend post-op!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies the key tissues that preferentially consume the increased glucose produced during the catabolic state following surgery or injury. The body prioritizes glucose for obligate glucose consumers and metabolically active healing tissues.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFollowing trauma or surgery, the body enters a catabolic state characterized by increased counter-regulatory hormones (e.g., cortisol, glucagon, catecholamines) which promote gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis. This newly synthesized glucose is critical for tissues that are obligate or preferential glucose consumers. The central nervous system (CNS) relies almost exclusively on glucose for energy. The renal medulla, due to its anaerobic metabolism, also primarily uses glucose. Crucially, the healing wound, with its high metabolic activity, inflammation, and cellular proliferation (e.g., fibroblasts, immune cells), has a significant demand for glucose as its primary fuel source for energy and synthetic processes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Skeletal muscle, while capable of using glucose, primarily shifts to utilizing fatty acids as its main fuel source during stress and fasting states to spare glucose for other critical tissues.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bone primarily utilizes mineral substrates for its structural integrity and has a relatively low metabolic rate compared to other tissues, not being a primary consumer of newly synthesized glucose.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tissue             | Primary Fuel Source (Post-Injury/Stress) |\n|--------------------|------------------------------------------|\n| Central Nervous System | Glucose (obligate)                       |\n| Healing Wound      | Glucose (high demand)                    |\n| Renal Medulla      | Glucose (preferential)                   |\n| Skeletal Muscle    | Fatty Acids (preferential)               |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-injury, glucose fuels the brain, kidney medulla, and the healing wound.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question pertains to metabolic physiology and does not directly involve imaging or intraoperative findings. No specific imaging or intraoperative pearl is applicable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThis is a fundamental physiology question and does not directly relate to a specific clinical guideline. It underpins principles found in general surgical nutrition and metabolism texts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Central nervous system. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Skeletal muscle. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bone. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Kidney. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Tissue in the healing wound. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ADE) Glucose is produced in increased amounts to satisfy the\nfuel requirements of the healing wound. In a** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
