  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Squeeze a bleeder, not a failing heart!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C because a pneumatic antishock garment (PASG) is contraindicated in cardiogenic shock. PASG increases systemic vascular resistance and venous return, which would worsen the failing heart's workload and compromise cardiac output further.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCardiogenic shock is characterized by severe pump failure, leading to inadequate tissue perfusion. The primary goal of treatment is to improve myocardial contractility, reduce cardiac workload, and optimize cardiac output. Dobutamine is a positive inotrope that directly enhances contractility, while sodium nitroprusside reduces both preload and afterload, thereby decreasing the heart's oxygen demand and improving forward flow. The intra-aortic balloon pump (IABP) provides mechanical circulatory support by reducing afterload and increasing coronary perfusion, directly addressing the core issues of pump failure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Dobutamine is a positive inotrope that increases myocardial contractility and heart rate, directly improving cardiac output in a failing heart.\nOption B (Incorrect): Sodium nitroprusside is a vasodilator that reduces both preload and afterload, decreasing the workload on the failing heart and improving forward flow.\nOption D (Incorrect): An intra-aortic balloon pump (IABP) is a mechanical circulatory support device that reduces afterload and increases coronary perfusion, directly assisting the failing ventricle.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Intervention | Mechanism in Cardiogenic Shock | Effect |\n|---|---|---|\n| Dobutamine | Beta-1 agonist | Increases contractility, cardiac output |\n| Sodium Nitroprusside | Vasodilator (arterial/venous) | Decreases preload/afterload, reduces workload |\n| Intra-aortic Balloon Pump | Mechanical support | Decreases afterload, increases coronary perfusion |\n| PASG | External compression | Increases afterload, venous return (contraindicated) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Don't squeeze a failing heart; PASG is for hypovolemia, not cardiogenic shock.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging in cardiogenic shock often reveals global hypokinesis or regional wall motion abnormalities on echocardiography, pulmonary edema on chest X-ray, and potentially signs of the underlying cause (e.g., large myocardial infarction). The question does not contain an image.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2017 ACC/AHA/HFSA Focused Update of the 2013 ACCF/AHA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure. This guideline provides recommendations for the management of acute decompensated heart failure, including cardiogenic shock, emphasizing early revascularization, inotropic support, and mechanical circulatory support.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Dobutamine. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Sodium nitroprusside. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pneumatic antishock garment. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Intra-aortic balloon pump. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) DISCUSSION: Cardiogenic shock occurs when the heart fails to generate adequate cardiac output to mai** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
