  "question": "43. The most common cause of fatal transfusion reactions is:",
  "options": {
    "A": "An allergic reaction.",
    "B": "An anaphylactoid reaction.",
    "C": "A clerical error.",
    "D": "An acute bacterial infection transmitted in blood."
  },
  "answer": "C) DISCUSSION: The most common cause of fatalities related to transfusion reactions result from ABO-incompatible transfusion related to clerical error. Most such reactions occur if a type O person receives type A red cells owing to a clerical error that occurs either at the time the blood sample was drawn, during processing in the laboratory, or at the time a unit is administered. The importance of extremely careful labeling, transfer, and handling of specimens and of cross-matched blood products cannot be overemphasized. Allergic and other reactions are common but rarely fatal. The transmission of bacterial organisms (e.g., Staphylococcus aureus) has been reported especially with platelet concentrates maintained at or near room temperature. Fortunately, such reactions are rare.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Double-check, double-check, or face double-trouble!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, a clerical error. This is because ABO-incompatible transfusions, almost always due to clerical errors, are the leading cause of fatal transfusion reactions, leading to acute hemolytic transfusion reactions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nClerical errors, such as mislabeling blood samples or administering the wrong unit, result in ABO incompatibility. When a patient receives ABO-incompatible blood, pre-existing antibodies (e.g., anti-A in a type O recipient receiving type A blood) rapidly bind to donor red blood cells, causing immediate and severe intravascular hemolysis. This triggers a systemic inflammatory response, leading to disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC), acute kidney injury, and shock, which can be rapidly fatal. The severity and rapid onset of these reactions distinguish them as the most lethal type.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): An allergic reaction is common but typically mild (e.g., urticaria, pruritus) and rarely fatal. Antihistamines usually manage these reactions effectively.\nOption B (Incorrect): An anaphylactoid reaction is a severe form of allergic reaction, but while serious, it is less common and less frequently fatal than ABO incompatibility dueating to clerical error. It often involves IgE-mediated mast cell degranulation.\nOption D (Incorrect): An acute bacterial infection transmitted in blood is a serious complication, particularly with platelet concentrates. However, it is a rare event due to stringent screening and processing, making it a less common cause of fatality compared to clerical errors.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Transfusion Reaction Type | Commonality | Fatality Risk | Primary Cause |\n|--------------------------|-------------|---------------|---------------|\n| ABO Incompatibility      | Rare        | High          | Clerical Error |\n| Allergic Reaction        | Common      | Low           | Plasma proteins |\n| Anaphylactoid Reaction   | Rare        | Moderate      | IgE-mediated |\n| Bacterial Contamination  | Very Rare   | Moderate      | Donor bacteremia/storage |\n| TRALI                    | Rare        | Moderate      | Donor antibodies |\n| TACO                     | Common      | Low           | Volume overload |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Clerical errors are the deadliest transfusion mistake.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, always perform a 'time-out' for blood product administration, visually verifying the patient's identity, blood type, and unit compatibility with a second person to prevent clerical errors.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAABB Standards for Blood Banks and Transfusion Services (2023) emphasizes strict patient identification and specimen labeling protocols to prevent ABO incompatible transfusions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | An allergic reaction. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | An anaphylactoid reaction. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | A clerical error. | ✅ Correct |\n| D | An acute bacterial infection transmitted in blood. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) DISCUSSION: The most common cause of fatalities related to transfusion reactions result from ABO-inc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
