  "question": "Glucose overload results in increased CO 2 production. Which of the following statements are true?",
  "options": {
    "A": "In patients with respiratory insufficiency, administration of glucose as a principal calorie source is contraindicated.",
    "B": "In patients with pulmonary infection and sepsis, calorie support should consist of 95% fat and 5% glucose.",
    "C": "In Askanazi's study, increased CO 2 production and difficulty in weaning was associated only with pronounced overfeeding.",
    "D": "CO 2 production should be measured in most patients who are supported by respirators in intensive care units and are receiving nutritional support."
  },
  "answer": "C) DISCUSSION: Few papers have excited as much interest as that by Askanazi, Kinney, and co-workers, which demonstrated that glucose calories given to patients with severe respiratory impairment may result in difficulty in weaning from a respirator. Subsequent research has suggested, however, that this occurs only with severe overfeeding, when the respiratory quotient is greater than 1 and calories are excessive. If one examines the conditions under which Askanazi's patients were studied, these were a group of septic, depleted patients who were taken from almost no nutritional support to a caloric supply of 2.25 times their caloric requirement, most of the calories consisting of glucose. Suffice it to say that, in patients with impaired respiratory function, one should measure VCO2 and, when VCO2 is significantly elevated and appears to interfere with weaning, decrease the amount of glucose calories and increase the amount of fat. If one measures or MedCosmos Surgery: MCQ : General Surgery http://medcosmossurgery.blogspot.com/search/label/MCQ : General Surgery 27 of 167 11-Aug-15 10:57 PM estimates calorie requirements and does not overfeed, lipid can be utilized for 25% of the caloric requirement and glucose for the remainder, without much fear of excessive CO 2 production.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed smart, not just more; CO2 production matters!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Askanazi's seminal work highlighted that increased CO2 production and subsequent difficulty in weaning from mechanical ventilation were primarily linked to pronounced overfeeding, particularly with excessive glucose, rather than glucose administration itself. Subsequent research clarified that moderate glucose intake within caloric needs is generally safe.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGlucose metabolism, especially when provided in excess of caloric needs, leads to a higher respiratory quotient (RQ > 1) compared to fat metabolism. This results in increased CO2 production (VCO2), which can exacerbate respiratory acidosis and make weaning from mechanical ventilation challenging, particularly in patients with compromised respiratory function. Askanazi's initial observations, while impactful, were based on patients receiving significantly supra-physiologic caloric loads, predominantly from glucose, thus demonstrating the critical importance of avoiding overfeeding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Administration of glucose as a principal calorie source is not absolutely contraindicated in patients with respiratory insufficiency, provided that caloric requirements are accurately estimated and overfeeding is avoided. The discussion explicitly states that glucose can be used for the majority of calories if not overfed.\nOption B (Incorrect): The suggested calorie support of 95% fat and 5% glucose is incorrect. Current recommendations and the discussion suggest a fat contribution of around 25% of total calories, with glucose making up the remainder, not an extreme fat-dominant diet.\nOption D (Incorrect): Routine measurement of CO2 production (VCO2) in 'most patients' on respirators is not standard practice. The discussion recommends measuring VCO2 specifically in patients with impaired respiratory function when elevated CO2 is suspected to interfere with weaning, not as a universal monitoring tool.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature                 | Pronounced Glucose Overfeeding (Askanazi's initial study) | Appropriate Nutritional Support (Current understanding) |\n| :---------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------ |\n| Caloric Intake          | ~2.25x estimated requirement                              | Estimated caloric requirement                           |\n| Glucose Contribution    | Principal source, excessive                               | ~75% of non-protein calories                            |\n| Fat Contribution        | Minimal                                                   | ~25% of non-protein calories                            |\n| CO2 Production (VCO2)   | Significantly elevated, RQ > 1                            | Managed, within physiological limits                    |\n| Weaning from Ventilator | Difficulty, prolonged                                     | Facilitated, no undue respiratory burden                |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Overfeeding, not just glucose, drives excess CO2 and weaning failure.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable as no image provided.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Critically Ill Patient (2016) recommend avoiding overfeeding and adjusting macronutrient ratios to minimize CO2 production in patients with respiratory compromise.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | In patients with respiratory insufficiency, administration of glucose as a  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | In patients with pulmonary infection and sepsis, calorie support should con | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | In Askanazi's study, increased CO 2 production and difficulty in weaning wa | ✅ Correct |\n| D | CO 2 production should be measured in most patients who are supported by re | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) DISCUSSION: Few papers have excited as much interest as that by Askanazi, Kinney, and co-workers, wh** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
