  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When one lung is a threat, isolate it with a DLT!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer accurately identifies the absolute indications for a double-lumen endotracheal tube (DLT) during thoracic surgery. These indications are paramount for patient safety, primarily to protect the healthy lung from contamination or to facilitate specific therapeutic interventions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAbsolute indications for DLT are driven by critical physiological and clinical needs for strict lung isolation. In cases of massive hemorrhage from one lung, isolation prevents blood spillage into the contralateral lung, averting aspiration and maintaining oxygenation. For unilateral lung infection, it prevents the spread of pathogens to the healthy lung. Unilateral bronchopulmonary lavage necessitates isolation to perform the procedure on one lung while maintaining ventilation of the other. These scenarios demand complete separation to ensure patient safety and optimize surgical outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): \"Facilitation of surgical exposure\" is a relative indication for a DLT. While it significantly improves the surgical field, it is not strictly necessary for patient safety or the completion of the procedure itself.\nOption E (Incorrect): \"All of the above\" is incorrect because option C is a relative, not an absolute, indication.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication Type | Examples | Primary Goal |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Absolute** | Massive hemorrhage, unilateral infection, bronchopleural fistula, unilateral lavage, pulmonary air cyst resection | Protect contralateral lung from contamination/spillage; manage complex ventilation |\n| **Relative** | Facilitation of surgical exposure (e.g., lobectomy, pneumonectomy, esophageal surgery), hypoxemia due to unilateral lung disease | Improve surgical field visibility; optimize ventilation/oxygenation in specific cases |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Absolute DLT indications protect the good lung from the bad.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn chest X-ray or CT, massive hemorrhage might appear as unilateral opacification or consolidation, while unilateral lung infection would show localized infiltrates or effusions. Intraoperatively, a DLT allows the surgeon to observe the collapsed lung and provides a clear, still surgical field, while the anesthesiologist can manage ventilation of the isolated lung.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Practice Guidelines for One-Lung Ventilation (e.g., 2021) provide recommendations for lung isolation techniques and indications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Massive hemorrhage from one lung. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Unilateral lung infection. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Facilitation of surgical exposure. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Unilateral bronchopulmonary lavage. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | All of the above. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: ABD) DISCUSSION: The absolute indications for a double-lumen tube are for the purposes of protecting one ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
