  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Safe discharge means stable, mobile, and protected.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Options B, C, and D correctly identify critical safety criteria for discharge following ambulatory surgery, ensuring the patient's immediate post-operative well-being and ability to manage at home. These criteria focus on physiological stability, airway protection, and basic functional recovery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStable vital signs (B) indicate physiological recovery from anesthesia and surgery, minimizing risks of cardiovascular or respiratory compromise. Protective airway reflexes (D) are paramount to prevent aspiration, especially given residual anesthetic effects and potential for nausea. The ability to ambulate (C) demonstrates sufficient motor recovery and reduces the risk of falls, allowing for basic self-care and mobility at home. These criteria collectively ensure the patient can safely transition from the surgical facility to home care, mitigating immediate post-operative risks.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The ability to eat solid food is generally not a prerequisite for discharge after ambulatory surgery. The ability to tolerate oral fluids without significant nausea or vomiting is typically sufficient to ensure adequate hydration and gastrointestinal recovery.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Discharge Criterion | Rationale for Ambulatory Surgery |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------- |\n| Stable Vital Signs  | Indicates physiological stability post-anesthesia/surgery. |\n| Protective Airway Reflexes | Prevents aspiration, crucial for airway patency. |\n| Ability to Ambulate | Demonstrates motor recovery, reduces fall risk, allows basic self-care. |\n| Oral Fluid Tolerance | Ensures hydration, not solid food. |\n| Adequate Pain Control | Essential for comfort and recovery at home. |\n| Responsible Adult Escort | Ensures safe transport and initial home care. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stable vitals, protective reflexes, and mobility are non-negotiable for ambulatory discharge.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Guidelines for Postanesthesia Care (2019) recommend specific criteria for discharge from Phase II recovery, including stable vital signs, adequate pain control, absence of significant nausea/vomiting, and ability to ambulate if appropriate for the procedure.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ability to eat solid food. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Stable vital signs. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ability to ambulate. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Ability to have protective airway reflexes. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: BCD) Discharge criteria following ambulatory surgery include the\npatient's being fully awake and oriented** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
