  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ketorolac: A powerful pain reliever, but respect its 5-day rule and renal wrath!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is AC. Ketorolac is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) with multiple approved routes of administration, making option A correct. However, like all NSAIDs, it carries risks such as renal dysfunction, validating option C.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nKetorolac tromethamine is a potent NSAID that provides effective analgesia by inhibiting cyclooxygenase (COX) enzymes, thereby reducing prostaglandin synthesis. This mechanism accounts for its anti-inflammatory and analgesic properties. While beneficial for pain control, COX inhibition also impacts renal blood flow regulation and platelet aggregation, leading to potential renal dysfunction and increased bleeding risk, respectively. Its FDA approval for intravenous, intramuscular, and oral routes makes it versatile for acute pain management, but its use is strictly limited to 5 days to mitigate these significant side effects.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Ketorolac should not be used indefinitely; guidelines recommend a maximum of 5 consecutive days due to the risk of significant side effects like renal and gastrointestinal complications.\nOption D (Incorrect): Ketorolac, by inhibiting platelet aggregation, can actually enhance surgical bleeding, not decrease it. This is a critical consideration in the perioperative setting.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ketorolac (NSAID) | Opioids | Acetaminophen |\n| :---------------- | :---------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------ |\n| Mechanism | COX inhibition | Mu-opioid receptor agonism | Central COX inhibition, other mechanisms |\n| Primary Use | Moderate-severe acute pain | Severe acute/chronic pain | Mild-moderate pain, antipyretic |\n| Key Side Effects | GI bleed, renal dysfunction, platelet dysfunction, increased bleeding risk | Respiratory depression, constipation, nausea, addiction | Hepatotoxicity (high dose), rare skin reactions |\n| Duration Limit | 5 days (post-op) | Variable, risk of dependence | Max 4g/day |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ketorolac is a powerful NSAID, but remember its 5-day limit and renal/bleeding risks.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, careful consideration of ketorolac use is paramount, especially in patients with pre-existing renal impairment or those undergoing procedures with high bleeding risk. While not directly visualized, its effects could manifest as increased intraoperative blood loss or postoperative renal insufficiency, requiring close monitoring of urine output and coagulation parameters.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEnhanced Recovery After Surgery (ERAS) Society Guidelines (e.g., 2019 for Colorectal Surgery) recommend multimodal analgesia including NSAIDs like ketorolac, but emphasize careful patient selection and short-term use to minimize adverse effects.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Is a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) approved for\nintravenous,  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Can be used indefinitely for postoperative analgesia. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Can cause renal dysfunction. | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | May decrease surgical blood loss. | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: AC) Ketorolac tromethamine, an NSAID, is approved by the FDA\nfor intravenous, intramuscular, and oral ad** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
