  "question": "Which of the following statement(s) is/are true concerning DNA?",
  "options": {
    "A": "DNA is contained only in the nucleus of the cell",
    "B": "DNA strands are encoded by the sequence of four bases—adenine, guanine, cytosine and uridine",
    "C": "The basic unit of information of DNA is the intron, a sequence of three bases",
    "D": "There are an infinite number of possible codons"
  },
  "answer": "a) The genetic blueprint of an organism is carried in the nucleus of every cell, encoded by the sequence of four bases—adenine, guanine, cytosine and thymine, which together make up two long chains bound together by hydrogen bonds to form a DNA double helix. A gene is a segment of DNA that is transcribed into a corresponding RNA molecule that either codes for a protein or forms a structural RNA molecule. Genes are commonly between 10,000 and 100,000 base pairs in length and include, in addition to the coding sequence, flanking regions and intervening sequences, termed introns. Introns are removed from the primary RNA transcript by a process called splicing. The basic unit of information is the codon, a sequence of three bases or triplet. The four nucleotide bases arranged as triplets lead to 64 possible codons. Sixty-one of these code for amino acids and three are termination signals called stop codons.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 DNA: Nucleus, Thymine, Codons are triplets, 64 possibilities.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer highlights that DNA, the genetic blueprint of an organism, is primarily housed within the nucleus of eukaryotic cells. This fundamental principle underpins cellular function and heredity, distinguishing DNA's primary location from other cellular components.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDNA, structured as a double helix, is composed of two strands linked by hydrogen bonds, with its information encoded by the sequence of adenine, guanine, cytosine, and thymine bases. This genetic material is predominantly found within the nucleus, where it forms genes that are transcribed into RNA, ultimately guiding protein synthesis or forming structural RNA molecules. This central and protected location ensures the regulated expression and integrity of the organism's genetic blueprint.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While the nucleus is the primary location for DNA, mitochondria also contain their own DNA. However, in the context of general statements about the organism's genetic blueprint, the nucleus is the main repository.\nOption B (Incorrect): DNA strands are encoded by adenine, guanine, cytosine, and thymine. Uridine is a base found in RNA, replacing thymine.\nOption C (Incorrect): The basic unit of information in DNA is the codon, a sequence of three bases. Introns are non-coding intervening sequences within genes that are removed during RNA processing.\nOption D (Incorrect): There are 64 possible codons (4 bases taken 3 at a time, 4^3), which is a finite number, not infinite.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature          | DNA                                     | RNA                                          |\n| :--------------- | :-------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------- |\n| Primary Location | Nucleus (also mitochondria)             | Cytoplasm (also nucleus, ribosomes)          |\n| Sugar            | Deoxyribose                             | Ribose                                       |\n| Bases            | Adenine, Guanine, Cytosine, Thymine     | Adenine, Guanine, Cytosine, Uracil           |\n| Structure        | Double helix                            | Single strand (can fold into complex shapes) |\n\n| Term      | Definition                                                              | Role                                                                |\n| :-------- | :---------------------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------------------ |\n| Codon     | A sequence of three nucleotide bases                                    | Basic unit of genetic information, codes for an amino acid or stop signal |\n| Intron    | Non-coding intervening sequence within a gene                           | Removed from primary RNA transcript during splicing                 |\n| Exon      | Coding segment of a gene                                                | Joined together after intron removal to form mature mRNA            |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: DNA is primarily nuclear, uses thymine, and codons are triplets, not introns.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNot applicable as this question is theoretical/molecular biology based.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nN/A (Basic science question)\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | DNA is contained only in the nucleus of the cell | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | DNA strands are encoded by the sequence of four bases—adenine, guanine, cyt | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The basic unit of information of DNA is the intron, a sequence of three bas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | There are an infinite number of possible codons | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a) The genetic blueprint of an organism is carried in the nucleus of every cell, encoded by the sequenc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
