  "question": "Which of the following statement(s) is/are true concerning cell membrane receptors?",
  "options": {
    "A": "The largest family of cell surface receptors are the G-protein-linked receptors",
    "B": "Activities of the G-protein involve binding and hydrolysis of ATP",
    "C": "The G protein receptor generates an intracellular messenger commonly through the use adenylate cyclase",
    "D": "Tyrosine kinase receptors are considered G-protein-linked receptors"
  },
  "answer": "a, c) All water-soluble regulatory molecules bind to the cell surface receptor proteins. Binding of the appropriate ligand evokes an intracellular signal which usually regulates enzyme activity, membrane transport, or in some cases gene expression. Most cell surface receptors belong to one of three functional classes—these are ion channel receptors, catalytic receptors, and G-protein-linked receptors. Ion channel receptors are multisubunit assemblies which, with each subunit, have a multiple membrane spanning segment. Together these subunits form an ion-selected pore that can be gated by a change in transmembrane electrical potential or binding of a ligand to one of the subunits. Catalytic receptors are membrane proteins that possess enzymatic activity. The best understood receptors of this class are the tyrosine kinases. The largest family of cell surface receptors are the G-protein-linked receptors. G-proteins are a family of proteins that bind and hydrolyze GTP. The final component of single transduction by G-protein-linked cell surface receptors is the effector that generates the intracellular messenger. The two best understood effectors are adenylate cyclase, which converts ATP to cAMP, and the polyphosphoinositi",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 G-proteins: GTP is their key, not ATP!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT because options A and C accurately describe key characteristics of cell membrane receptors. G-protein-linked receptors constitute the largest family of cell surface receptors, and their signaling often involves effectors like adenylate cyclase to generate intracellular messengers.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCell surface receptors are crucial for cellular communication, allowing water-soluble regulatory molecules to evoke intracellular signals. These receptors are broadly categorized into ion channel, catalytic (like tyrosine kinases), and G-protein-linked receptors. G-protein-linked receptors are particularly significant due to their abundance and their mechanism involving G-proteins that bind and hydrolyze GTP, ultimately activating effectors such as adenylate cyclase to produce secondary messengers like cAMP, thereby regulating various cellular processes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): G-proteins bind and hydrolyze GTP, not ATP, as part of their activation and deactivation cycle in signal transduction.\nOption D (Incorrect): Tyrosine kinase receptors are a type of catalytic receptor, which is a distinct class from G-protein-linked receptors. They possess intrinsic enzymatic activity, unlike G-protein-linked receptors which activate separate G-proteins.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Receptor Type | Key Feature | Ligand Binding | Intracellular Action | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Ion Channel | Forms ion-selective pore | Ligand or voltage-gated | Ion flow, membrane potential change | Nicotinic acetylcholine receptor |\n| Catalytic | Intrinsic enzymatic activity | Ligand binding activates enzyme | Phosphorylation, enzymatic cascade | Tyrosine kinase receptors (e.g., Insulin receptor) |\n| G-Protein-Linked | Coupled to G-proteins | Ligand binding activates G-protein | G-protein activates effector (e.g., adenylate cyclase) | Adrenergic receptors |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: G-proteins use GTP, not ATP, to signal.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question pertains to molecular biology and cellular physiology; therefore, there is no direct imaging or intraoperative pearl.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThis question addresses fundamental cell biology and receptor physiology, not a specific surgical procedure or clinical guideline.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The largest family of cell surface receptors are the G-protein-linked recep | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Activities of the G-protein involve binding and hydrolysis of ATP | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The G protein receptor generates an intracellular messenger commonly throug | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Tyrosine kinase receptors are considered G-protein-linked receptors | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, c) All water-soluble regulatory molecules bind to the cell surface receptor proteins. Binding of the ap** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
