  "id": 201481,
  "question": "Which of the following statement(s) is/are true concerning nutritional support of the injured patient?",
  "options": {
    "A": "The goal of nutritional support is maintenance of body cell mass and limitation of weight loss to less than 25% of preinjury weight",
    "B": "Under-nutrition may compromise the patient’s available defense mechanisms",
    "C": "Nutritional support is an immediate priority for the trauma patient",
    "D": "Fifty percent of non-nitrogen caloric requirements should be provided in the form of fat"
  },
  "answer": "B) Metabolic response to injury results in increased energy expenditure. If energy intake is less than expenditure, oxidation of body fat stores and erosion of lean body mass will occur with resultant loss of weight. When weight loss exceeds 10–15% of body weight, the complications of malnutrition interact with disease processes, with increased morbidity and mortality rates. The goal of nutritional support is maintenance of body cell mass and limitation of weight loss to less than 10% preinjury. The major impact of nutritional support in the trauma patient is to aid host defense. Under-nutrition may compromise the available host defense mechanism and may thus increase the likelihood of invasive sepsis, multiple organ system failure, and death. Resuscitation, oxygenation and arrest of hemorrhage are immediate priorities for survival. Nutritional support is an essential part of the metabolic care of the critically ill patient and should be instituted after resuscitation before significant weight loss occurs. The nutritional requirements of a trauma patient can be determined by determining basal metabolic rate with appropriate increases based on extent of injury and hospital activity. After initial determination of nitrogen requirements, caloric requirements should be distributed at a ratio of 70% as glucose and 30% as fat.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed the injured to fight the infection.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, highlighting that under-nutrition significantly compromises the injured patient's defense mechanisms. This is crucial because adequate nutritional status directly impacts the body's ability to mount an effective immune response and recover from trauma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe metabolic response to injury leads to increased energy expenditure, and if caloric intake is insufficient, the body catabolizes lean body mass and fat stores. This erosion of lean body mass, particularly immune cells and structural proteins, directly impairs host defense mechanisms. Malnutrition, especially when weight loss exceeds 10-15%, increases susceptibility to infections, sepsis, multiple organ system failure, and ultimately, higher morbidity and mortality rates. Therefore, nutritional support is not just about maintaining weight, but fundamentally about preserving immune function and aiding recovery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The goal of nutritional support is to limit weight loss to less than 10-15% of preinjury weight, not 25%. Exceeding 10-15% weight loss significantly increases complications.\nOption C (Incorrect): While essential, nutritional support is not an immediate priority for the trauma patient; immediate priorities are resuscitation, oxygenation, and hemorrhage control to ensure survival.\nOption D (Incorrect): Caloric requirements for trauma patients should typically be distributed with 70% as glucose and 30% as fat, not 50% fat.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Aspect of Nutritional Support | Correct Principle | Incorrect/Misconception |\n|------------------------------|-------------------|-------------------------|\n| **Weight Loss Threshold**    | < 10-15%          | > 25%                   |\n| **Immediate Priority**       | Resuscitation, Hemorrhage Control | Nutritional Support     |\n| **Fat Caloric Contribution** | 30%               | 50%                     |\n| **Primary Goal**             | Maintain Host Defense, Limit Lean Body Mass Loss | Just maintain weight    |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prioritize ABCs, then feed to preserve immunity.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question does not involve imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Critically Ill Patient (2016) recommend early enteral nutrition in critically ill patients to preserve gut integrity and modulate immune response.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The goal of nutritional support is maintenance of body cell mass and limita | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Under-nutrition may compromise the patient’s available defense mechanisms | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Nutritional support is an immediate priority for the trauma patient | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Fifty percent of non-nitrogen caloric requirements should be provided in th | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Metabolic response to injury results in increased energy expenditure. If energy intake is less than ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
