  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed the gut first; TPN is a last resort.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption E is correct because all other statements (A, B, C, D) contain inaccuracies or overgeneralizations regarding nutritional support in cancer patients. Effective nutritional support is highly individualized and depends on the patient's nutritional status, type of cancer, and planned treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNutritional support in cancer patients is a critical adjunct to therapy, aiming to prevent or reverse malnutrition, improve tolerance to treatment, and enhance quality of life. However, it is not universally indicated for all patients or via a single route. Preoperative nutritional support is specifically beneficial for malnourished patients or those undergoing major resections, typically for 7-14 days, to reduce postoperative complications. Enteral nutrition is generally preferred over parenteral nutrition as it maintains gut integrity, reduces infection risk, and is more physiological. Parenteral nutrition is reserved for patients with a non-functional gastrointestinal tract.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Preoperative nutritional support is not indicated for all cancer patients. It is primarily recommended for patients who are malnourished or at high nutritional risk, or those undergoing major upper gastrointestinal surgery.\nOption B (Incorrect): While a duration of 7-14 days is often cited for effective preoperative nutritional support, stating 'at least two weeks' is an oversimplification and not universally required for all patients to see benefits. The optimal duration varies.\nOption C (Incorrect): Enteral nutrition is the preferred route of feeding for most cancer patients if the gut is functional, due to its physiological benefits, lower cost, and fewer complications compared to parenteral nutrition.\nOption D (Incorrect): Standard total parenteral nutrition (TPN) solutions do not maintain the integrity of the small bowel. In fact, prolonged TPN can lead to gut mucosal atrophy, impaired barrier function, and bacterial translocation. Enteral feeding is crucial for maintaining gut health.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Enteral Nutrition (EN) | Parenteral Nutrition (PN) | Preoperative Nutrition |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Route | Oral, tube (NG, G-tube) | Intravenous | Oral, EN, or PN |\n| Gut Integrity | Maintains, prevents atrophy | Does not maintain, can lead to atrophy | Indicated for malnourished patients |\n| Preference | Preferred if gut functional | Used when gut non-functional | Improves outcomes in select high-risk patients |\n| Complications | Aspiration, diarrhea | Infection, metabolic, liver dysfunction | Reduces complications in specific groups |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Individualize cancer nutrition; prioritize the gut, use TPN judiciously.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo imaging or intraoperative findings are directly relevant to this question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN (American Society for Parenteral and Enteral Nutrition) Guidelines for Nutrition Support in Cancer Patients (e.g., 2021) recommend individualized nutritional assessment and support, prioritizing the enteral route when feasible.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Preoperative nutritional support should be provided to all patients with ca | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | To be effective, preoperative nutrition must be given for at least two week | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Parenteral nutrition is the preferred route of feeding for all cancer patie | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Standard total parenteral nutrition solutions maintain integrity of the sma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) The role of nutritional support in the cancer patient remains an important component of overall ther** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
