  "question": "102 Which of the following hormones can be expected to be released as part of the stress response?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Antidiuretic hormone (ADH)",
    "B": "Aldosterone",
    "C": "Insulin",
    "D": "Epinephrine"
  },
  "answer": "a, b, d) Several important responses occur in response to stress. The body immediately attempts to compensate for a reduction in circulating blood volume in order to maintain adequate organ perfusion. Afferent nerve signals are also initiated which stimulate the release of both antidiuretic hormone (ADH) and aldosterone. The pain and fear associated with the stress response lead to excessive production to catecholamines which also increase metabolic rate, stimulate lipolysis, hepatic glycolysis, and gluconeogenesis. Glucagon, which has a potent glycogenolytic and gluconeogenic effect in the liver, is also released. This hormone has the exact opposite effect of insulin, which promotes glucose storage and uptake by the cells.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Stress: ADH, Aldosterone, Epi surge; Insulin takes a dive!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies multiple hormones released during the body's stress response. The body initiates a complex neurohumoral cascade to maintain homeostasis, particularly circulating blood volume and energy supply, in the face of stress.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuring stress, afferent nerve signals stimulate the release of antidiuretic hormone (ADH) from the posterior pituitary, which increases water reabsorption in the kidneys to conserve fluid. Aldosterone, released from the adrenal cortex, is also stimulated to increase sodium and water reabsorption, further supporting blood volume. The pain and fear associated with stress trigger the sympathetic nervous system, leading to the release of catecholamines like epinephrine from the adrenal medulla, which increases heart rate, blood pressure, and mobilizes energy stores through glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Insulin promotes glucose uptake and storage by cells, which is the opposite effect needed during a stress response where the body requires rapid glucose mobilization for energy. During stress, insulin levels typically decrease, while counter-regulatory hormones like glucagon, epinephrine, and cortisol increase to raise blood glucose.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Gland/Source | Primary Effect in Stress Response |\n|---|---|---|\n| Antidiuretic Hormone (ADH) | Posterior Pituitary | Increases water reabsorption in kidneys, maintains blood volume |\n| Aldosterone | Adrenal Cortex | Increases Na+ and water reabsorption in kidneys, maintains blood volume and blood pressure |\n| Epinephrine | Adrenal Medulla | Increases heart rate, blood pressure, mobilizes glucose (glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis) |\n| Glucagon | Pancreas (alpha cells) | Increases blood glucose (glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Stress hormones conserve fluid and mobilize energy; insulin is suppressed.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question pertains to systemic endocrine physiology rather than imaging or intraoperative findings. No specific imaging or intraoperative pearl is directly applicable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThis is a fundamental physiology question and is not directly tied to a specific surgical society guideline. It represents core knowledge for understanding patient responses to surgical stress.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Antidiuretic hormone (ADH) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Aldosterone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Insulin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Epinephrine | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, d) Several important responses occur in response to stress. The body immediately attempts to compensate** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
