  "id": 201497,
  "question": "A 59-year-old trauma patient has suffered multiple septic complications including severe pneumonia, intraabdominal abscess, and major wound infection. He has now developed signs of multisystem organ failure. Which of the following statement(s) is/are true concerning necessary changes to be made in his nutritional management?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Carbohydrate load should be reduced in the face of respiratory failure",
    "B": "In patients with renal failure, protein intake should be diminished",
    "C": "During hemodialysis protein intake should be limited to the same extent",
    "D": "In patients with hepatic failure, carbohydrate load should be increased"
  },
  "answer": "a, b) The most severe complication of sepsis is multiple system organ dysfunction syndrome, which may result in death. The development of organ failure requires changes in the nutritional requirements and creates special feeding problems. A problem associated with systemic infection is oxygenation and elimination of carbon dioxide. Most of the enteral and parenteral formulas used to provide nutritional support for critically ill patients contain large amounts of carbohydrate, which generate large amounts of carbon dioxide following oxygenation. Such a large CO2 load may worsen pulmonary function or may delay weaning from the respirator. If this factor becomes a problem, the carbohydrate load should be reduced to 50% of metabolic requirements and fat emulsion administered to provide additional calories. When renal failure becomes progressive, the use of hemodialysis minimizes the effect of uremia superimposed on the metabolism of sepsis. Metabolic studies in patients with acute and chronic renal failure have limited the intake of nonessential amino acids, in an attempt to lower urea production. Proteins of high biologic value, but in much smaller quantities than usually given, are administered along with adequate calories, usually in the form of glucose. When enteral feedings are not feasible, a central venous infusion of an essential amino acid solution and hypertonic dextrose provides calories and a small quantity of nitrogen to reduce protein catabolism while simultaneously controlling the rise in BUN. During dialysis, protein intake is liberalized, but the BUN should still be maintained below 100 mg/dl. Hepatic dysfunction is a common manifestation of septicemia. The carbohydrate load is usually reduced to consist of no more than 5% of metabolic requirements, and the additional calories should be provided as fat emulsion. If encephalopathy develops, protein load should also be reduced0.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Organ failure dictates nutritional changes; don't feed the fire!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies that nutritional management in a critically ill patient with multisystem organ failure requires specific adjustments tailored to the failing organ systems. Options A and B are true because they reflect necessary modifications to carbohydrate and protein intake to mitigate metabolic burdens on compromised respiratory and renal function, respectively.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIn respiratory failure, reducing carbohydrate load is crucial because carbohydrate metabolism generates a significant amount of carbon dioxide, which can exacerbate respiratory distress and hinder ventilator weaning. Fat emulsions are used to provide alternative calories. For renal failure, protein intake must be carefully managed to limit urea production, a byproduct of protein metabolism, which can worsen uremia. High biologic value proteins are given in smaller quantities, and essential amino acid solutions are used when enteral feeding is not possible, to reduce protein catabolism while controlling BUN levels.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): During hemodialysis, protein intake is typically liberalized, not limited, because dialysis removes urea and other nitrogenous wastes, allowing for higher protein intake to support recovery and prevent malnutrition.\nOption D (Incorrect): In hepatic failure, especially with encephalopathy, carbohydrate load should be reduced, not increased, to no more than 5% of metabolic requirements, with additional calories provided as fat emulsion. Increased carbohydrate load can worsen metabolic derangements in a failing liver.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Organ Failure | Nutritional Adjustment | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Respiratory Failure | Reduce carbohydrate load (to 50% of metabolic needs); increase fat emulsion | Minimize CO2 production, ease ventilator weaning |\n| Renal Failure (pre-dialysis) | Diminish protein intake (high biologic value, small quantities); adequate glucose | Limit urea production, control BUN |\n| Renal Failure (on dialysis) | Liberalize protein intake | Dialysis removes nitrogenous waste, allows for higher protein needs |\n| Hepatic Failure | Reduce carbohydrate load (to 5% of metabolic needs); increase fat emulsion | Prevent worsening metabolic derangements, especially encephalopathy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Tailor nutrition to organ failure: less carbs for lungs, less protein for kidneys (pre-dialysis).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question does not involve specific imaging findings or intraoperative pearls. The focus is on metabolic and nutritional management in a critically ill patient.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN/SCCM Guidelines for the Provision and Assessment of Nutrition Support Therapy in the Adult Critically Ill Patient (2016) recommend specific macronutrient adjustments based on organ dysfunction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Carbohydrate load should be reduced in the face of respiratory failure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | In patients with renal failure, protein intake should be diminished | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | During hemodialysis protein intake should be limited to the same extent | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | In patients with hepatic failure, carbohydrate load should be increased | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b) The most severe complication of sepsis is multiple system organ dysfunction syndrome, which may resu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
