  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed the fight, not the futility.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOptions C and D are correct. TPN is appropriately used in cancer patients who are severely malnourished prior to surgery or other therapy, or when treatment toxicities prevent adequate enteral nutrition, ensuring essential support when the GI tract is compromised.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe rationale for TPN in cancer patients centers on providing critical nutritional support when the gastrointestinal tract is non-functional or insufficient. This is vital for severely malnourished patients undergoing major interventions like surgery, or when anti-cancer treatments (chemotherapy, radiation) induce severe GI toxicity, making enteral feeding impossible. Crucially, TPN should be reserved for patients expected to benefit from anti-tumor therapy, not those with rapidly progressing, unresponsive disease, as it carries inherent risks without clinical benefit in such scenarios.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Long-term TPN is contraindicated in patients with rapidly progressive tumor growth unresponsive to therapy, as it offers no benefit and carries significant risks. The text explicitly states this.\nOption B (Incorrect): TPN is not indicated for mildly malnourished patients, especially if they are expected to resume adequate oral intake within approximately seven days. The risks of TPN outweigh the benefits in this population.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Indication for TPN in Cancer |\tContraindication for TPN in Cancer |\n| :---------------------------- |\t:--------------------------------- |\n| Severe malnutrition pre-op/therapy |\tMild malnutrition |\n| Treatment toxicity precluding enteral nutrition for >7 days |\tRapidly progressive tumor unresponsive to therapy |\n| Expected response to anti-tumor therapy |\tExpected to resume adequate enteral nutrition within 7 days |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: TPN for cancer patients: severe malnutrition or GI toxicity, not for mild cases or unresponsive tumors.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo imaging or intraoperative findings are provided or relevant to this question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe provided text does not explicitly name a specific guideline. However, general principles align with recommendations from major surgical and oncology societies regarding nutritional support.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Long-term TPN in patients with rapid progressive tumor growth\nunresponsive  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mildly malnourished patients undergoing surgery for a curable cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Preoperatively administered TPN prior to surgery or other therapy in\npatien | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Patients in whom treatment toxicity precludes the use of enteral\nnutrition | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: c, d) As a general rule, the most important factor to consider when making\ndecisions about the use of TPN ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
