  "id": 201506,
  "question": "A number of prospective clinical trials have addressed the role of total parenteral nutrition in the cancer patient. The results have been somewhat conflicting. Which of the following statement(s) have been proven correct by prospective trials?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Preoperative TPN is beneficial in surgical patients with severe preoperative nutrition",
    "B": "Postoperative TPN is of value following pancreatic resection",
    "C": "Routine use of perioperative (including prior to the procedure) TPN is of benefit in patients undergoing hepatectomy for hepatoma",
    "D": "TPN is of no benefit in patients undergoing bone marrow transplant"
  },
  "answer": "a, c) Numerous clinical trials have failed to yield a consensus with regard to the efficacy of TPN in cancer patients. In 1991, a multicenter VA cooperative trial demonstrated that preoperative TPN is of benefit in surgical patients (many of whom had cancer) with severe preoperative malnutrition. Another study examined the use of routine postoperative TPN following major pancreatic resection. Patients randomized to receive TPN starting on postoperative day 1 were noted to have an increased incidence of intra-abdominal abscesses as well as a tendency towards increased incidence in peritonitis and bowel obstruction. These investigators concluded that routine use of postoperative TPN was not indicated and may, in fact, be harmful following pancreatic resection. In another study, however, perioperative (starting 7 days prior to the planned procedure) TPN for patients undergoing hepatectomy for hepatocellular carcinoma demonstrated that this regimen statistically reduced infectious complications compared to patients who did not receive TPN. This was one of the few studies that demonstrated that routine TPN (without the requirement of severe preoperative malnutrition) was of benefit. The use of TPN in patients receiving bone marrow transplantation has also been shown to be a valuable component of overall care.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 TPN: Not for everyone, but a lifesaver for some.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies specific scenarios where total parenteral nutrition (TPN) has demonstrated proven benefits in cancer patients through prospective clinical trials. The role of TPN is not universal and depends heavily on patient-specific factors and the surgical context.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOption A is correct because the 1991 multicenter VA cooperative trial demonstrated that preoperative TPN is beneficial in surgical patients, many with cancer, who present with severe preoperative malnutrition. This highlights the importance of nutritional optimization in a high-risk group. Option C is also correct, as a study on perioperative TPN (starting 7 days pre-op) for patients undergoing hepatectomy for hepatocellular carcinoma showed a statistically significant reduction in infectious complications, making it one of the few instances where routine TPN (without severe malnutrition) proved beneficial.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Routine postoperative TPN following major pancreatic resection has been shown to increase the incidence of intra-abdominal abscesses, peritonitis, and bowel obstruction, indicating it is not beneficial and potentially harmful.\nOption D (Incorrect): TPN has been demonstrated to be a valuable component of overall care for patients undergoing bone marrow transplantation, contrary to the statement that it is of no benefit.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Scenario | TPN Benefit | Rationale/Outcome |\n|---|---|---|\n| Severely malnourished surgical patients (preoperative) | Yes | VA trial showed benefit, especially in high-risk patients |\n| Hepatectomy for Hepatocellular Carcinoma (perioperative) | Yes | Reduced infectious complications |\n| Routine postoperative pancreatic resection | No | Increased intra-abdominal abscesses, peritonitis, bowel obstruction |\n| Bone marrow transplant patients | Yes | Valuable component of overall care |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: TPN is not a panacea; target specific high-risk scenarios.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question does not include an image, so there is no specific imaging or intraoperative pearl to reference.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nASPEN/ESPEN Guidelines for Parenteral Nutrition in Oncology (2009/2017): Recommend TPN for malnourished cancer patients unable to meet nutritional needs enterally, especially preoperatively for major surgery, and in specific situations like bone marrow transplant.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Preoperative TPN is beneficial in surgical patients with severe preoperativ | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Postoperative TPN is of value following pancreatic resection | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Routine use of perioperative (including prior to the procedure) TPN is of b | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | TPN is of no benefit in patients undergoing bone marrow transplant | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, c) Numerous clinical trials have failed to yield a consensus with regard to the efficacy of TPN in canc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
