  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't rush to feed; sometimes less is more post-op.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. For most elective surgical patients without significant preoperative malnutrition, initial postoperative intravenous 5% dextrose solutions are adequate for a short period (5-7 days) without detrimental effects, despite not meeting full caloric needs.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe body's metabolic response to surgical stress involves catabolism, but for well-nourished patients undergoing elective surgery, endogenous stores (glycogen, fat, protein) can adequately bridge the initial postoperative period. Administering 5% dextrose provides minimal calories (approximately 500 kcal/day) to prevent ketosis and spare some protein, while avoiding the increased cost and potential complications (e.g., infection, metabolic derangements) associated with more aggressive nutritional support like total parenteral nutrition (TPN) or early full enteral feeding when not indicated. This approach prioritizes safety and cost-effectiveness for the typical surgical patient.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Routine preoperative immunologic testing (total peripheral lymphocyte count, delayed hypersensitivity reaction) is not standard practice for all patients to assess nutritional status, especially when no preoperative deficit is noted. These tests are generally reserved for specific high-risk or severely malnourished patients.\nOption C (Incorrect): Intravenous 5% glucose solutions, typically administered at rates like 125 cc/hour, provide approximately 500 kcal/day, which is significantly less than the basal energy requirements for most adults, thus it cannot meet them.\nOption D (Incorrect): The placement of a jejunal feeding catheter for postoperative enteral feeding is not routinely indicated for all surgical patients, particularly those without extensive gastrointestinal surgery or anticipated prolonged ileus, as implied by the \"above-described patient\" who has no preoperative deficit.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nutritional Strategy | Caloric Provision | Indication (Typical Patient) | Considerations |\n| :------------------- | :---------------- | :--------------------------- | :------------- |\n| 5% Dextrose IV | ~500 kcal/day | Initial post-op for well-nourished, elective surgery | Prevents ketosis, spares protein; not full nutrition |\n| Enteral Nutrition | Full caloric needs | Functional GI tract, unable to eat orally, prolonged NPO | Preferred over TPN; maintains gut integrity |\n| Parenteral Nutrition | Full caloric needs | Non-functional GI tract, severe malnutrition, prolonged NPO | Higher cost, infection risk, metabolic complications |\n| Nutritional Assessment | N/A | Identify patients at risk for malnutrition | Weight loss (>10-15%), low albumin, specific disease states |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For most elective surgery, 5% dextrose is fine initially; don't overfeed.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A - No imaging or intraoperative details are provided in the question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nERAS Society Guidelines for Perioperative Care (e.g., 2019) recommend early oral feeding or enteral nutrition when feasible, but acknowledge that for short periods, simple IV fluids are acceptable in well-nourished patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Since the patient’s weight had been stable with no preoperative nutritional | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Preoperative immunologic status should be determined including total periph | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Routine postoperative fluid administration with intravenous 5% glucose solu | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A jejunal feeding catheter should be placed at the time of surgery for post | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a) Most patients undergoing elective operations are adequately nourished. Unless the patient has suffer** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
