  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just prescribe, assess the wound's true need!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question addresses a critical aspect of surgical practice: the judicious use of antibiotics in wound care. Not all open wounds require systemic antibiotics, and their indiscriminate use contributes to antibiotic resistance and potential adverse effects.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOptimal wound management prioritizes local care, including thorough irrigation, debridement of non-viable tissue, and appropriate dressing. Systemic antibiotics are reserved for specific indications such as established infection, grossly contaminated wounds (e.g., fecal contamination), high-risk wounds (e.g., human/animal bites, open fractures), or in immunocompromised patients. The decision to use antibiotics should be guided by the wound's characteristics, patient factors, and the risk of infection, not as a routine measure for all open wounds.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Systemic antibiotics are not indicated for all open wounds. Routine prophylactic use for clean, simple wounds is generally not recommended and can promote antibiotic resistance without significant clinical benefit.\nOption B (Incomplete): This option is incomplete and cannot be evaluated. Without the full statement, its correctness or incorrectness cannot be determined.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Wound Type/Scenario | Antibiotic Indication | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| Clean, simple laceration | No (unless high risk) | Low infection risk, local care sufficient |\n| Grossly contaminated wound | Yes (prophylactic/therapeutic) | High bacterial load, significant infection risk |\n| Established wound infection | Yes (therapeutic) | Treat active infection, guided by culture |\n| Human/animal bite wound | Yes (prophylactic) | High risk of polymicrobial infection |\n| Open fracture | Yes (prophylactic) | High risk of osteomyelitis and deep infection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Antibiotics are an adjunct, not a substitute, for meticulous wound care.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile imaging is not typically used for simple open wounds, for deeper or complex wounds, X-rays might reveal foreign bodies or underlying fractures, and CT/MRI could show abscesses or deep tissue involvement. Intraoperatively, the surgeon assesses tissue viability, contamination, and the presence of foreign material to guide debridement and antibiotic decisions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) and Infectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) guidelines for surgical site infection prevention and management provide recommendations on antibiotic prophylaxis and treatment in various surgical and wound scenarios.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Systemic antibiotics are indicated for all open wounds | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Bacterial resistan | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
