  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Scar smart: Know your boundaries, know your treatment.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D is correct because re-excision and improved closure can be an effective treatment for hypertrophic scars, particularly when the initial wound healed by secondary intention or was complicated by infection. This approach aims to optimize wound healing conditions and reduce scar burden.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHypertrophic scars, unlike keloids, respect the boundaries of the original injury and do not invade surrounding normal tissue. This characteristic makes them amenable to surgical revision, especially when the initial healing process was suboptimal. By re-excising and achieving a primary, tension-free closure, surgeons can improve the cosmetic and functional outcome of hypertrophic scars, leveraging the scar's inherent tendency to remain within the wound margins.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Keloids are not random; they predominantly affect dark-skinned individuals with a genetic predisposition, often transmitted in an autosomal dominant pattern.\nOption B (Incorrect): Histologically, keloids and hypertrophic scars are similar, both characterized by an overabundance of collagen, not distinct differences.\nOption C (Incorrect): Keloids typically develop several months to a year or more after injury, while hypertrophic scars often appear earlier, within weeks to months.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Keloid | Hypertrophic Scar |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Extent** | Extends beyond original injury boundaries | Respects original injury boundaries |\n| **Histology** | Similar to hypertrophic scar (abundant collagen) | Similar to keloid (abundant collagen) |\n| **Genetic Predisposition** | Strong (dark-skinned, autosomal dominant) | Less, but more frequent in Orientals/Black population |\n| **Development Time** | Several months to a year or more post-injury | Weeks to months post-injury |\n| **Re-excision** | Unpredictable, potentially worse outcome | Can be useful, especially for secondary intention or infected wounds |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Keloids grow beyond, hypertrophic scars stay within.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a keloid would be observed as a firm, raised, often pruritic lesion extending well beyond the original wound margins, sometimes with claw-like projections. A hypertrophic scar, conversely, would be raised and firm but confined strictly to the boundaries of the initial injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInternational Clinical Recommendations on Scar Management: 2023 Update by the International Advisory Panel on Scar Management recommends surgical excision for hypertrophic scars and keloids, often combined with adjuvant therapies like intralesional steroids or radiation for keloids, and emphasizes optimizing wound closure for hypertrophic scars.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Keloids occur randomly regardless of gender or race | ❌ Incorrect |\n| b | Hypertrophic scars and keloid are histologically different | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | Keloids tend to develop early and hypertrophic scars late after the surgica | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | Simple reexcision and closure of a hypertrophic scar can be useful in certa | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: d) True keloids are uncommon and occur predominantly in dark skinned people with a genetic predispositi** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
