  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Target the clot, save the limb, minimize the bleed!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nACCEPT. This answer correctly identifies key aspects of intraarterial thrombolytic therapy for peripheral arterial occlusion, including the initial high-dose infusion, subsequent maintenance dose, and specific indications for its use, particularly when surgical clot removal is incomplete.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraarterial thrombolysis offers a targeted approach to dissolve arterial thrombi by delivering fibrinolytic agents directly into the clot. This direct delivery maximizes local drug concentration, enhancing clot lysis efficacy while minimizing systemic exposure and the associated risk of bleeding complications compared to intravenous administration. The initial high-dose bolus rapidly initiates fibrinolysis, followed by a lower maintenance dose to sustain the lytic process. Its utility extends to situations where surgical thrombectomy is incomplete or technically challenging, ensuring optimal revascularization.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption c (Incorrect): The usual infusion time for intraarterial thrombolysis is typically 6-12 hours, with a reported mean of 18 hours, not usually in excess of 24 hours.\nOption d (Incorrect): Successful clot lysis is significantly more frequent in native arterial occlusions (77%) compared to arterial graft occlusions (41%), contrary to the statement.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Intraarterial Thrombolysis (Peripheral) | Intravenous Thrombolysis (e.g., PE/Stroke) | Surgical Thrombectomy |\n| :---------------------- | :--------------------------------------- | :----------------------------------------- | :-------------------- |\n| **Delivery Method** | Direct into clot via catheter | Systemic infusion | Mechanical removal |\n| **Bleeding Risk** | Lower systemic, higher local | Higher systemic | Localized |\n| **Target** | Peripheral arterial thrombi | Pulmonary emboli, ischemic stroke | Acute arterial occlusion |\n| **Success Rate (Native vs. Graft)** | Higher in native arteries (77% vs 41% in grafts) | N/A | Variable |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intraarterial thrombolysis: targeted, high-dose start, lower maintenance, better for native arteries.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nAngiographic guidance is crucial for precise catheter placement directly into the thrombus, allowing for real-time monitoring of clot lysis and identification of underlying lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2016 AHA/ACC Guideline on the Management of Patients With Lower Extremity Peripheral Artery Disease recommends catheter-directed thrombolysis for acute limb ischemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | A standard technique involves infusing high-dose urokinase, 4000 units per  | ✅ Correct |\n| b | If progress is made, further fibrinolytic therapy is given at 1000 to 2000  | ✅ Correct |\n| c | The usual infusion time by the above-stated technique is usually in excess  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | Successful clot lysis occurs more frequently in arterial graft occlusions t | ❌ Incorrect |\n| e | The use of intraoperative thrombolytic therapy may be indicated for situati | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, e) The most popular method for intraarterial thrombolytic therapy for arterial occlusion involves passi** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
