  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't get tangled in the clot; know your lytics'ytics' quirks!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key differentiating features of thrombolytic agents. Streptokinase, being a bacterial protein, is antigenic, while TPA acts directly on plasmin, and streptokinase remains a significantly more affordable option.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThrombolytic therapy relies on activating plasminogen to plasmin, which then degrades fibrin clots. Streptokinase, derived from bacteria, forms a complex with plasminogen to activate it, making it antigenic and prone to allergic reactions. In contrast, tissue plasminogen activator (TPA) and urokinase are human-derived or recombinant, acting directly on plasminogen without forming an intermediate complex, thus avoiding antigenicity. While all three agents effectively induce a lytic state, their half-lives are generally short, typically less than 30 minutes. Cost remains a significant factor, with streptokinase being considerably cheaper than TPA or urokinase, despite comparable efficacy in many clinical scenarios.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption c (Incorrect): The half-lives of urokinase, streptokinase, and TPA are all less than 30 minutes, not exceeding 30 minutes as stated in the option. This short duration necessitates continuous infusion for sustained thrombolysis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Streptokinase | Urokinase | Tissue Plasminogen Activator (TPA) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Origin | Bacterial protein | Human renal cells / Recombinant | Recombinant |\n| Antigenicity | Yes (2-18% allergic reactions) | No | No |\n| Mechanism | Forms complex with plasminogen | Direct activation of plasminogen | Direct activation of plasminogen |\n| Half-life | < 30 minutes | < 30 minutes | < 30 minutes |\n| Cost | Least expensive | Intermediate | Most expensive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Streptokinase is cheap and antigenic; TPA is direct and expensive.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nThis question does not involve imaging or intraoperative findings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Heart Association (AHA) / American Stroke Association (ASA) Guidelines for the Early Management of Patients with Acute Ischemic Stroke (2019) recommend intravenous alteplase (TPA) within 4.5 hours of symptom onset for eligible patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Streptokinase is a bacterial protein which is antigenic in humans, resultin | ✅ Correct |\n| b | Tissue plasminogen activator acts directly on plasmin without an intermedia | ✅ Correct |\n| c | The half-life of urokinase, streptokinase, and TPA all exceed 30 minutes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | Streptokinase is significantly cheaper than urokinase or TPA | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b, d) Streptokinase is a bacterial protein produced by group C b-hemolytic streptococci. It is therefore a** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
