  "question": "Laboratory monitoring of coagulation and anticoagulation includes testing of platelet function. Which of the following statements is/are true concerning tests of platelet function?",
  "options": {
    "A": "A platelet count of 50,000/µL or more usually ensures hemostasis",
    "B": "Bleeding time assays assessibility of platelets to perform hemostatic plugs and is determined from a sample of blood drawn in an EDTA coated test tube",
    "C": "Aspirin therapy can be associated with a bleeding time in the range of 8–15 minutes",
    "D": "Tests of platelet aggregation should be part of the standard preoperative evaluation of patients using aspirin"
  },
  "answer": "A, C) Tests of platelet function include peripheral platelet counts, bleeding times, and platelet aggregation. Usually, a platelet count of 50,000/mL or more ensures adequate hemostasis, whereas counts less than 10,000/mL are dangerous and may lead to spontaneous bleeding. Bleeding time performed by observing the clotting of blood induced with a small needle stick, assesses the ability of platelets to perform hemostatic plugs and are usually shorter than eight minutes. A bleeding time between 8 and 15 minutes most often reflects a low plasma level of Von Willebrand’s Factor or the use of antiplatelet drugs. A bleeding time greater than 15 minutes is clearly prolonged and indicates severe platelet functional impairment. Platelet aggregation studies involve the use of a number of different agonists. Although a relatively straightforward technique, platelet aggregation is not available in most laboratories, probably because of the observer-dependent nature",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Platelets: quantity and quality matter for hemostasis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer highlights two crucial aspects of platelet function: the minimum platelet count generally required for adequate hemostasis and the expected impact of aspirin on bleeding time. A platelet count of 50,000/µL is typically sufficient for surgical hemostasis, and aspirin's antiplatelet effect commonly prolongs bleeding time into the 8-15 minute range.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPlatelet function is fundamental to primary hemostasis, involving adhesion, activation, and aggregation to form a platelet plug. A peripheral platelet count directly measures the number of circulating platelets, with 50,000/µL being a critical threshold for preventing excessive bleeding during surgery. The bleeding time assay, though less frequently used now, assesses the *in vivo* ability of platelets to form this plug. Aspirin irreversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase-1 (COX-1), preventing the synthesis of thromboxane A2, which is essential for platelet aggregation, thereby prolonging the bleeding time.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Bleeding time assays assess *in vivo* platelet function by observing the time it takes for a standardized skin incision to stop bleeding, not from a blood sample drawn in an EDTA tube. EDTA is an anticoagulant used for cell counts, not functional coagulation tests.\nOption D (Incorrect): While platelet aggregation studies evaluate platelet function, they are not considered part of the *standard* preoperative evaluation for patients using aspirin. This is due to their limited availability, technical demands, and the fact that clinical history and simpler tests often suffice for risk assessment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Test | Purpose | Normal Range | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Platelet Count | Quantifies circulating platelets | 150,000-450,000/µL | <50,000/µL increases bleeding risk; <10,000/µL spontaneous bleeding |\n| Bleeding Time | Assesses *in vivo* platelet plug formation | <8 minutes | Prolonged by antiplatelets (e.g., aspirin), VWD, severe thrombocytopenia |\n| Platelet Aggregation | Measures platelet response to agonists | Varies by agonist | Detects inherited/acquired platelet disorders, antiplatelet drug effects |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: 50k platelets for surgery, aspirin prolongs bleeding time.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo imaging or intraoperative findings are directly relevant to this question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Practice Guidelines for Perioperative Blood Management (2015) recommend assessing bleeding risk based on patient history and physical exam, with laboratory testing reserved for specific indications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A platelet count of 50,000/µL or more usually ensures hemostasis | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Bleeding time assays assessibility of platelets to perform hemostatic plugs | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Aspirin therapy can be associated with a bleeding time in the range of 8–15 | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Tests of platelet aggregation should be part of the standard preoperative e | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C) Tests of platelet function include peripheral platelet counts, bleeding times, and platelet aggregat** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
