  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let Candida take hold; protect the transplant, but don't forget the host!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies that prophylaxis against Candida is crucial in immunocompromised patients, especially those on prolonged antibiotics, and that severe Candida bacteremia necessitates a reduction in immunosuppression. These principles are fundamental to managing opportunistic infections in transplant recipients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nImmunocompromised patients, such as renal transplant recipients on prolonged antibiotics, are highly susceptible to opportunistic fungal infections like Candida. Prophylaxis with oral antifungals like nystatin is a cornerstone of preventing these infections, particularly during periods of maximal immunosuppression. Furthermore, in the face of virulent Candida bacteremia, reducing immunosuppressive agents is a critical step to allow the host immune system to mount an effective response, thereby improving infection control and patient survival.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption b (Incorrect): A Candida urinary tract infection can often be treated with oral antifungals or topical amphotericin B bladder irrigation, not necessarily systemic amphotericin B, which is reserved for more severe or disseminated infections.\nOption c (Incorrect): Changes of Candida retinitis are highly significant, as they indicate disseminated infection and are an indication for systemic antifungal therapy (e.g., a limited course of amphotericin B).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Candida Infection Type | Management Strategy | Rationale |\n| :------------------- | :------------------ | :-------- |\n| Prophylaxis (high risk) | Oral nystatin | Prevents opportunistic infection in immunocompromised/prolonged antibiotics |\n| Localized UTI | Oral antifungal or topical amphotericin B bladder irrigation | Targets infection locally, avoids systemic toxicity |\n| Retinitis/Disseminated | Systemic amphotericin B | Indicates severe, invasive infection requiring aggressive treatment |\n| Virulent Bacteremia | Reduce immunosuppression + Systemic antifungals | Enhances host immunity, crucial for clearing severe infection in transplant patients |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Immunosuppression reduction is key for severe Candida in transplant patients.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor Candida retinitis, fundoscopic examination would reveal characteristic white, fluffy lesions with indistinct borders, often associated with vitreous haze. In the OR, peritoneal candidiasis might present with white plaques on serosal surfaces, requiring biopsies for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Candidiasis (2016) recommends prophylaxis in high-risk patients and dose reduction of immunosuppressants for severe infections.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| a | Due to the potential risk of Candida infection, prophylaxis with oral nysta | ✅ Correct |\n| b | A Candida urinary tract infection should be treated with systemic amphoteri | ❌ Incorrect |\n| c | Changes of Candida retinitis are of little significance | ❌ Incorrect |\n| d | The presence of a virulent Candida bacteremia should suggest a dosage reduc | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, d) Infections due to fungal pathogens have become increasingly common during the past decade, frequentl** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
