  "id": 201639,
  "question": "Which of the following statement(s) is/are true concerning continuous arteriovenous hemofiltration (CAVH)?",
  "options": {
    "A": "The technique runs continuously",
    "B": "It is not associated with the hemodynamic instability",
    "C": "Systemic heparin anticoagulation is necessary",
    "D": "Fluid balance and correcting electrolyte abnormalities takes several days"
  },
  "answer": "a, b) Continuous arteriovenous hemofiltration (CAVH) is an extracorporial filtration technique that removes extracellular fluid across a synthetic membrane via hydrostatic pressure gradient created between the indwelling arterial and venous catheters. Arteriovenous access is accomplished by percutaneous cannulation of femoral artery and vein with a low incidence of complications. Although full systemic anticoagulation is not necessary for CAVH, heparinization of the extracorporial circuit is required. CAVH is run continuously for as many days as renal replacement is required. Experience with CAVH has demonstrated very little or no hemodynamic instability with treatment of critically ill renal failure patients. The stable nature of this therapy is attributed to a slow and continuous fluid and solute removal and to the fact that the membrane does not induce compliment activation when in contact with blood. Fluid balance and serum electrolyte concentrations can be titrated to any level in a matter of hours by manipulating the composition and rate of replacement solution. Solute clearance with CAVH is limited by the ultrafiltration and replacement fluid exchange rate. In patients with high urea generation rates, solute removal with CAVH may be inadequate and variations of the technique may be used to enhance clearance.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CAVH: slow and steady wins the race for unstable kidneys.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct options A and B highlight that Continuous Arteriovenous Hemofiltration (CAVH) is a continuous renal replacement therapy known for its hemodynamic stability. This makes it a preferred method for critically ill patients who cannot tolerate rapid fluid and solute shifts.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCAVH operates continuously, leveraging the patient's own arterial pressure to drive blood through an extracorporeal circuit and filter, creating a hydrostatic pressure gradient. This slow, sustained removal of fluid and solutes, typically over several days, minimizes rapid hemodynamic changes often seen with intermittent therapies. Furthermore, the synthetic membranes used in CAVH are designed to reduce complement activation, contributing to its stable profile in critically ill patients.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption C (Incorrect): Systemic heparin anticoagulation is not necessary for CAVH; only heparinization of the extracorporeal circuit is typically required to prevent clotting within the filter.\nOption D (Incorrect): Fluid balance and serum electrolyte concentrations can be precisely titrated and corrected within a matter of hours by adjusting the replacement solution, not several days.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Continuous Arteriovenous Hemofiltration (CAVH) | Intermittent Hemodialysis (IHD) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Mechanism** | Arteriovenous pressure gradient | Blood pump |\n| **Duration** | Continuous (days) | Intermittent (hours) |\n| **Hemodynamic Stability** | High (slow, gentle removal) | Lower (rapid fluid/solute shifts) |\n| **Anticoagulation** | Circuit heparinization (systemic often avoided) | Systemic heparin often required |\n| **Fluid/Electrolyte Control** | Gradual, precise (hours) | Rapid, can cause disequilibrium |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CAVH: continuous, stable, and gentle for the critically ill.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPercutaneous cannulation of the femoral artery and vein is typically performed to establish arteriovenous access for the CAVH circuit.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO 2012 Clinical Practice Guideline for Acute Kidney Injury recommends continuous renal replacement therapies (CRRT) over intermittent RRT for hemodynamically unstable patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The technique runs continuously | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is not associated with the hemodynamic instability | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Systemic heparin anticoagulation is necessary | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Fluid balance and correcting electrolyte abnormalities takes several days | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b) Continuous arteriovenous hemofiltration (CAVH) is an extracorporial filtration technique that remove** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
