  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Feed the kidneys, save the patient; nonoliguric is often less dire.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B and D. This question assesses understanding of metabolic and management principles in acute renal failure (ARF) post-aortic aneurysm repair, particularly focusing on nutritional support and prognostic indicators. Maintaining positive energy balance is crucial to mitigate catabolism, and nonoliguric ARF generally portends a better prognosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute renal failure in a critically ill patient, especially post-surgery, significantly alters metabolic demands. The body enters a hypercatabolic state, increasing resting energy expenditure. Providing adequate exogenous calories through positive energy balance reduces the reliance on endogenous protein breakdown, thereby minimizing urea generation and potassium release, which are critical in managing uremia and hyperkalemia. Furthermore, the distinction between oliguric and nonoliguric ARF is prognostically important; nonoliguric forms often indicate less severe renal damage, are more frequently reversible, and require less aggressive interventions like renal replacement therapy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Resting energy expenditure in critically ill patients with acute renal failure is typically *increased*, often 50% above normal, not less.\nOption C (Incorrect): While hyperkalemia is a serious concern, expected metabolic abnormalities in ARF commonly include *hypocalcemia* and *metabolic acidosis*, not hypercalcemia and metabolic alkalosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Oliguric ARF | Nonoliguric ARF |\n|---|---|---|\n| Urine Output | < 400 mL/24h | > 400 mL/24h |\n| Prognosis | Generally worse | Generally better |\n| Reversibility | Less likely | More likely |\n| RRT Need | More frequent | Less frequent |\n| Management | More complex fluid/electrolyte | Often similar to normal renal function |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Positive energy balance in ARF reduces catabolism; nonoliguric ARF is often reversible.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo imaging is provided or directly relevant to the metabolic and management aspects of this question.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes (KDIGO) Clinical Practice Guideline for Acute Kidney Injury (2012) recommends nutritional support to meet energy requirements and avoid protein-energy wasting in AKI patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Resting energy expenditure will likely be less than would be expected for a | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Maintenance of positive energy balance reduces protein catabolism and makes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Expected metabolic abnormalities include hyperkalemia, hypercalcemia, and m | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A nonoliguric renal failure is usually associated with a better outcome | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b, d) In patients with nonoliguric renal failure, treatment may differ little from that required for ident** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
