  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't drown the elderly, hydrate the young!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A and C. These statements accurately reflect standard maintenance fluid calculations, recognizing the typical daily water needs for an adult and the physiological adjustments required for elderly patients due to their reduced tolerance for fluid overload.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMaintenance IV fluid therapy aims to replace normal daily fluid and electrolyte losses without addressing pre-existing deficits or ongoing abnormal losses. The total body water (TBW) percentage is higher in younger and smaller individuals, necessitating a greater fluid requirement per kilogram compared to larger adults. Conversely, elderly patients often have decreased cardiac reserve and renal function, making them more susceptible to complications from fluid overload, thus requiring a reduced maintenance fluid volume.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Normal maintenance IV therapy primarily requires sodium and potassium. Calcium, phosphate, and magnesium are generally not needed for short-term maintenance unless specific deficits are identified, especially in critically ill patients.\nOption D (Incorrect): A child (smaller individual) has a higher percentage of total body water relative to body weight and a higher metabolic rate, thus requiring a greater amount of maintenance fluid per kilogram than a larger individual.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Factor | Younger/Smaller Individual | Older/Larger Individual |\n| :------------------------- | :----------------------- | :---------------------- |\n| TBW % | Higher | Lower |\n| Fluid/kg requirement | Higher | Lower |\n| Tolerance to hypervolemia | Better | Poorer |\n| Electrolytes for maintenance | Na, K | Na, K |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Maintenance fluid is about normal daily losses, not deficits. Adjust for age and size.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nN/A\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNICE guideline [CG174] on intravenous fluid therapy in adults in hospital (2013, updated 2017) recommends specific fluid types and amounts for maintenance, emphasizing individualized assessment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The total daily water requirement for a 70-kg man is about 2500 mL/day | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Normal maintenance IV therapy requires administration of sodium, potassium, | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Fluid volume calculations for elderly patients generally are decreased comp | ✅ Correct |\n| D | A child requires a lesser amount of maintenance fluid per kilogram than a l | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A, C) Maintenance fluid replacement is aimed at replacing fluids normally lost during the course of a day.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
