  "question": "Which of the following statement(s) is/are true concerning abnormalities in serum potassium?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Hyperkalemia can occur in the otherwise normal surgical patient due to excessive intravenous potassium administration",
    "B": "The primary EKG change associated with severe hyperkalemia is peaked T-waves",
    "C": "Temporary treatment of hyperkalemia includes administration of calcium, sodium bicarbonate, or glucose and insulin",
    "D": "Alterations in membrane potentials reflected in cardiac and skeletal muscle are common results of both hypo-and hyperkalemia",
    "E": "A reduction in serum potassium of 1mEq/liter requires replacement of 40mEq of potassium"
  },
  "answer": "c, d) Potassium is the major intracellular cation and is a major determinant MedCosmos Surgery: MCQ : General Surgery http://medcosmossurgery.blogspot.com/search/label/MCQ : General Surgery 153 of 167 11-Aug-15 10:57 PM of intracellular osmolality. Because of the large differences between intracellular and extracellular potassium concentrations, a transmembrane potential is generated. Alterations in potassium concentration gradient (both hyper- and hypokalemia) have profound effects on transmembrane potential and consequently on cellular function. This is especially true for cardiac, skeletal, and smooth muscle. Extracellular potassium concentration is primarily determined by renal excretion. About 90% of ingested potassium is secreted by the urine. Hyperkalemia therefore rarely develops from excessive potassium intake in the absence of renal insufficiency, since the capacity for renal potassium excretion is large. In the surgical patient, diminished renal function is perhaps the most common problem leading to hyperkalemia. Both chronic and acute renal failure result in the deficit in potassium excretion. Hyperkalemia can also be associated with cellular disruption, such as with crush injuries or lysed erythrocytes in large hematomas or after massive blood transfusion. The clinical manifestations of hyperkalemia are primarily related to membrane depolarization. The most life-threatening manifestations are related to the cardiac effects of membrane depolarization. Mild hyperkalemia results in peake",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Potassium: The heart's rhythm keeper, handle with care!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies that both temporary treatments for hyperkalemia and the profound effects of potassium abnormalities on membrane potentials are true statements. Understanding potassium's role in cellular function is critical for managing surgical patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPotassium is the primary intracellular cation, crucial for maintaining transmembrane potential, especially in excitable tissues like cardiac and skeletal muscle. Alterations in its concentration gradient, whether hyper- or hypokalemia, directly impact this potential, leading to significant cellular dysfunction. Temporary treatments for hyperkalemia aim to shift potassium intracellularly or stabilize cardiac membranes, buying time for definitive removal.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hyperkalemia rarely develops from excessive potassium administration in an otherwise normal surgical patient with intact renal function, as the kidneys have a large capacity for excretion. Renal insufficiency is typically a prerequisite.\nOption B (Incorrect): While peaked T-waves are an early and primary EKG change in hyperkalemia, in *severe* hyperkalemia, more advanced and life-threatening changes like QRS widening, PR prolongation, and loss of P waves become prominent. Stating peaked T-waves as *the* primary change for *severe* hyperkalemia is an oversimplification.\nOption E (Incorrect): A 1 mEq/L reduction in serum potassium typically reflects a much larger total body deficit, often requiring 100-200 mEq or more of potassium replacement, not just 40 mEq, due to the vast intracellular stores.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hyperkalemia | Hypokalemia |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Causes** | Renal failure, cellular lysis (crush injury, rhabdomyolysis), acidosis, certain medications (ACEi, spironolactone) | Diuretics, GI losses (vomiting, diarrhea), hyperaldosteronism, insulin, alkalosis |\n| **EKG Changes** | Peaked T-waves, PR prolongation, QRS widening, absent P waves, sine wave, asystole | U-waves, flattened T-waves, ST depression, prolonged QT interval |\n| **Temporary Treatment** | Calcium gluconate (membrane stabilization), insulin/glucose, sodium bicarbonate, beta-agonists (intracellular shift) | Oral or IV potassium replacement |\n| **Definitive Treatment** | Diuretics, potassium binders, dialysis | Address underlying cause, continued replacement |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Potassium abnormalities profoundly affect cardiac and muscle function; treat the patient, not just the number.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nNo imaging or intraoperative findings are directly applicable to this question, as it focuses on serum electrolyte abnormalities and their systemic effects.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes (KDIGO) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Evaluation and Management of Chronic Kidney Disease (2012) recommends careful monitoring and management of electrolyte disturbances, including potassium, in patients with CKD.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hyperkalemia can occur in the otherwise normal surgical patient due to exce | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The primary EKG change associated with severe hyperkalemia is peaked T-wave | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Temporary treatment of hyperkalemia includes administration of calcium, sod | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Alterations in membrane potentials reflected in cardiac and skeletal muscle | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | A reduction in serum potassium of 1mEq/liter requires replacement of 40mEq  | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: c, d) Potassium is the major intracellular cation and is a major determinant MedCosmos Surgery: MCQ : Gene** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "c, d"
