  "question": "277 Which of the following statement(s) is/are true concern renal tubular acidosis?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Renal tubular acidosis is primarily caused by reduction in ammonia excretion",
    "B": "The renal tubular defect in renal tubular acidosis can either be at the distal or proximal renal tubule",
    "C": "In distal renal tubular acidosis associated with hyperkalemia, the defect involves increased tubular permeability with backleak of secreted sodium and potassium into the tubular cell",
    "D": "Uremic acidosis occurs independently of protein intake"
  },
  "answer": "a, b) The impaired ability of the kidney to excrete acid and hence generate bicarbonate may be secondary to a decrease in the number of functioning nephrons and is termed uremic acidosis or renal tubular acidosis. Renal tubular acidosis, which can occur both in acute and chronic renal failure, is primarily caused by reduction in ammonia excretion secondary to a reduction in the number of functioning proximal tubular cells. In addition, decreased proximal tubular bicarbonate reabsorption contributes to the development of acidosis. Although the onset of uremic acidosis is related to declining renal function, its appearance may be influenced by diet-dependent protein and organic anion ingestion. Renal tubular acidosis may be classified as distal or proximal, depending on the primary site of the renal tubular defect leading to acidosis. In renal tubular acidosis with hyperkalemia, the mechanism is decreased luminal negativity secondary to impaired sodium reabsorption. In distal renal tubular acidosis with hypokalemia, mechanisms including increased tubular permeability with backleak of secreted H+ into the tubular cell and reduced H+ pump activity are proposed mechanisms.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 RTA: When kidneys forget how to acid-base.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOptions A and B are correct. Renal tubular acidosis (RTA) is characterized by the kidney's inability to excrete acid, primarily due to reduced ammonia excretion, and the defect can originate in either the proximal or distal renal tubules.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRTA represents a critical failure in renal acid-base homeostasis. The primary mechanism involves a reduction in ammonia excretion, often stemming from a decreased number of functioning proximal tubular cells, which are crucial for ammonia synthesis and secretion. Additionally, impaired bicarbonate reabsorption in the proximal tubule can exacerbate the acidosis. The classification of RTA into proximal or distal types is based on the specific segment of the nephron where the primary defect in acid handling occurs, dictating the clinical presentation and management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Correct): Renal tubular acidosis is indeed primarily caused by a reduction in ammonia excretion, as stated in the provided explanation.\nOption B (Correct): The renal tubular defect in RTA can be classified as either distal or proximal, depending on the primary site of the defect.\nOption C (Incorrect): In hyperkalemic RTA, the mechanism involves decreased luminal negativity due to impaired sodium reabsorption, not increased tubular permeability with backleak of secreted sodium and potassium. Backleak of H+ is associated with hypokalemic dRTA.\nOption D (Incorrect): Uremic acidosis is influenced by diet-dependent protein and organic anion ingestion, meaning it does not occur independently of protein intake.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Type 1 (Distal) RTA | Type 2 (Proximal) RTA | Type 4 (Hyperkalemic) RTA |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Defect | Impaired H+ secretion in distal tubule | Impaired HCO3- reabsorption in proximal tubule | Aldosterone deficiency/resistance or impaired Na+ reabsorption in distal tubule |\n| Serum K+ | Usually low | Usually low | High |\n| Urine pH | > 5.5 | Variable, can be < 5.5 if severe | < 5.5 |\n| Cause | Genetic, autoimmune, drugs | Genetic, Fanconi syndrome, drugs | Diabetes, interstitial nephritis, drugs |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: RTA: Ammonia excretion and location are key to diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging for RTA may reveal nephrocalcinosis in distal RTA or underlying renal pathology such as hydronephrosis or chronic kidney disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO Clinical Practice Guideline for the Evaluation and Management of Chronic Kidney Disease (2012) recommends assessing acid-base status in CKD patients and managing metabolic acidosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Renal tubular acidosis is primarily caused by reduction in ammonia excretio | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The renal tubular defect in renal tubular acidosis can either be at the dis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | In distal renal tubular acidosis associated with hyperkalemia, the defect i | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Uremic acidosis occurs independently of protein intake | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: a, b) The impaired ability of the kidney to excrete acid and hence generate bicarbonate may be secondary t** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
  "verified_answer": "a, b"
