  "id": 201662,
  "question": "279 Which of the following statement(s) is/are true concerning parenternal electrolyte solutions?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Lactated Ringer’s solution contains physiologic concentrations of all important electrolytes",
    "B": "Glucose is added to hypotonic saline solutions to increase their tonicity",
    "C": "About 1/2 of all exogenously administered albumin ends up in the extravascular space",
    "D": "Normal saline solution provides excessive sodium and chloride which may lead to body sodium overload"
  },
  "answer": "b, c, d) A number of electrolytes solutions are available for parenteral administration. Lactated Ringer’s solution is a physiologic solution containing many of the electrolytes found in plasma. The disadvantage of this solution is the relatively low sodium content (130 mEq/L) as compared to plasma. Hyponatremia can occur with extended use of lactated Ringer’s solution. Isotonic saline (0.9% or normal saline) contains 154 mEq of both sodium and chloride. The excess of both sodium and chloride can lead to electrolyte and acid-base disturbances. Infusion of large volumes of 0.9% saline can lead to total body sodium overload and hyperchloremia. The less-concentrated saline solutions are hypo-osmotic and have excess free water. In addition, 0.2% saline solution is hypotonic with respect to plasma and can result in red blood cell lysis if rapidly infused. For this reason, 5% dextrose is added to these solutions to increase the tonicity. Plasma expanders are commonly used in surgical patients. Plasma protein solutions such as 5% and 25% albumin act initially by increasing plasma oncotic pressures. Abnormalities in microvascular permeability such as those found in the pulmonary circulation in adult respiratory distress syndrome, in regional circulatory bed burns or infections, and in the systemic circulation in sepsis, may result in extravasation of these proteins into the interstitial space. About half of all exogenously administered albumin eventually ends up in the extravascular space. The half life of exogenously administered albumin is about 11 days.",
  "chapter": "Review",
  "specialty": "Review",
  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fluid choice matters: not all 'saline' is created equal!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies key characteristics and potential complications of commonly used parenteral electrolyte solutions and albumin. Options B, C, and D are true, highlighting important considerations for fluid and electrolyte management in surgical patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGlucose is added to hypotonic saline solutions (like 0.2% saline) to increase their tonicity, preventing red blood cell lysis which can occur with rapid infusion of highly hypotonic solutions. Exogenously administered albumin, while initially increasing plasma oncotic pressure, is known to extravasate into the interstitial space, especially in conditions of increased microvascular permeability, with approximately half ending up extravascularly. Normal saline (0.9% NaCl) contains supraphysiologic concentrations of sodium (154 mEq/L) and chloride (154 mEq/L), which can lead to total body sodium overload, hyperchloremic metabolic acidosis, and other electrolyte disturbances with large volume infusions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lactated Ringer’s solution does not contain physiologic concentrations of all important electrolytes. Specifically, its sodium content (130 mEq/L) is lower than plasma (135-145 mEq/L), and prolonged use can lead to hyponatremia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Solution Type | Key Characteristic | Clinical Implication |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lactated Ringer's | Hypotonic Na (130 mEq/L) | Risk of hyponatremia with prolonged use |\n| Normal Saline (0.9% NaCl) | Hypertonic Na/Cl (154 mEq/L each) | Risk of hyperchloremic acidosis, Na overload |\n| Hypotonic Saline + Dextrose | Dextrose increases tonicity | Prevents RBC lysis from hypotonicity |\n| Albumin (exogenous) | Plasma expander, oncotic agent | ~50% extravasates, especially with capillary leak |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know the electrolyte profile and potential pitfalls of common IV fluids.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn chest X-ray, fluid overload from excessive parenteral solutions may manifest as pulmonary edema (e.g., Kerley B lines, perihilar haziness). In the OR, excessive fluid administration can lead to tissue edema, especially in the bowel, potentially complicating abdominal closure.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Practice Guidelines for Perioperative Fluid Management (2022) recommends individualized fluid therapy, balancing crystalloids and colloids based on patient needs and avoiding excessive sodium and chloride loads.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lactated Ringer’s solution contains physiologic concentrations of all impor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Glucose is added to hypotonic saline solutions to increase their tonicity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | About 1/2 of all exogenously administered albumin ends up in the extravascu | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Normal saline solution provides excessive sodium and chloride which may lea | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: b, c, d) A number of electrolytes solutions are available for parenteral administration. Lactated Ringer’s so** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: 699910936-MedCosmos-Surgery-MCQ-General-Surgery.pdf**\n",
